// SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0 WITH LLVM-exception
//
// test/parse/recovery/error-in-seq-then-module-item.test — M2 Phase
// 5 / US3 (T051 of `specs/005-m2-parser/tasks.md`).
//
// **Specification anchors**:
//   - spec.md US3 acceptance scenario 3: "Given an input containing
//     a malformed expression inside a `module`'s `seq` block, when
//     the parser runs, then the diagnostic is emitted, the parser
//     recovers at the `;` or the matching `}`, and the rest of the
//     `module`'s `module_item`s are still parsed and appear in the
//     AST."
//   - parser-recovery.contract.md §"Multi-error fixture corpus
//     minimum" item 3 + the recovery-set table row for
//     `parseSeqItem()`: `{Semi, RBrace, if, for, while, goto,
//     return}` — consume the `;` if matched.
//   - FR-021: recovery MUST cover seq-block-item at every site.
//
// The malformed expression is `x := y +` (binary `+` with no right
// operand). Per the contract's diagnostic-output examples, this
// raises `error: expected expression after binary operator`. The
// recovery scope — the `seq` block — has `;` and `}` in its set; the
// `}` of the `seq` block becomes the resume point. After unwinding
// out of the seq block, the parent `parseModuleItem()` loop iterates
// once more and parses the well-formed `reg q[8];` declaration.
//
// **What this fixture asserts (per the contract's "What recovery
// does NOT do" §)**: an error fired → NO AST on stdout. So the
// observable stderr surface is exactly ONE error line (the seq-block
// raise). The "subsequent well-formed `module_item` still appears in
// the AST" property is a unit-test concern (T053 — partial-AST
// preservation gtest).
//
// This fixture's load-bearing assertion is therefore:
//   - exactly ONE error-severity diagnostic on stderr,
//   - exit 1,
//   - the parser did NOT crash or emit further (cascaded) diagnostics
//     for the well-formed `reg q[8];` that follows the seq block.
//
// We use `// ERR-NOT: error: expected '}'` as a guard against a
// faulty recovery that mis-pairs braces and produces a cascade.
//
// **FR-029 / Principle VIII RED state evidence**: against parent
// commit `39cc618`, `parseSeqBlock()` propagates `nullptr` and the
// parent `parseProcDefn()` propagates further; recovery never
// resumes at the seq's `}`, so the parser may emit cascaded
// diagnostics or stop early. Either way the assertion below
// (well-defined "exactly one diagnostic; no cascade") fails.

// RUN: not %nslc -emit=ast %s 2>&1 | FileCheck %s --check-prefix=ERR

module foo {
    proc p {
        seq {
            x := y +
        }
    }
    // Well-formed `module_item` after the seq-block error. Recovery
    // resumes at the proc's `}`, then at the module-item dispatch
    // loop's iteration boundary; this declaration MUST parse without
    // a cascade.
    reg q[8];
}

// Exactly one error: the seq-block raise. Per the contract's
// "Diagnostic output during recovery" examples, the message is
// `expected expression after binary operator` — but since the exact
// text Track L lands may differ (per task description: "the
// integration patch reconciles"), we assert the prefix only.
// ERR: error: expected

// Guard against a cascade. After recovery, no further `error:` line
// MUST emit (the well-formed `reg q[8];` parses cleanly).
// ERR-NOT: error: expected '}'
// ERR-NOT: error: expected ';' after register declaration
